# 🌐 HTTP Methods

> **Module:** Web Security  
> **Lesson:** Day 4

---

## Introduction

An HTTP Method tells the server **what action the client wants to perform** on a resource.

Think of it as a command or instruction.

When a browser sends an HTTP request, the method tells the server whether it wants to:

- Retrieve information
- Submit data
- Update data
- Delete data
- Check information

Every HTTP request begins with a method.

Example:

```http
GET /products HTTP/1.1
```

Here:

- **GET** → Method
- **/products** → Resource
- **HTTP/1.1** → HTTP Version

---

# Why HTTP Methods Matter

Different actions require different methods.

Imagine an online shopping website.

| User Action | HTTP Method |
|-------------|-------------|
| View products | GET |
| Log in | POST |
| Update profile | PUT or PATCH |
| Delete account | DELETE |

Using the correct method makes web applications more organized, secure, and predictable.

---

# GET Method

The **GET** method is used to retrieve information from the server.

It should only read data and must not modify anything.

Example:

```http
GET /products HTTP/1.1
Host: example.com
```

Possible uses:

- Opening a webpage
- Viewing products
- Reading blog posts
- Searching for items

Example URL:

```text
/search?q=laptop
```

The query parameter is visible in the URL.

---

## Characteristics of GET

- Retrieves data
- Parameters are sent in the URL
- Can be bookmarked
- Can be cached
- Should never modify server data

---

## Security Consideration

Never send sensitive information using GET.

Bad Example:

```text
/login?username=admin&password=123456
```

This information may appear in:

- Browser history
- Server logs
- Shared URLs
- Proxy logs

---

# POST Method

POST is used to send data to the server.

Unlike GET, POST usually places data inside the request body.

Example:

```http
POST /login HTTP/1.1

username=soham
password=hello123
```

Common uses:

- Login
- Registration
- Contact forms
- Payments
- File uploads

---

## Characteristics of POST

- Sends data to the server
- Uses the request body
- Cannot be bookmarked
- Commonly used for creating new resources

---

# PUT Method

PUT replaces an existing resource completely.

Imagine your profile currently contains:

```text
Name : Soham
Age  : 20
City : Mumbai
```

A PUT request sends the complete updated profile.

```http
PUT /profile HTTP/1.1

Name=Soham
Age=21
City=Pune
```

The old profile is replaced entirely.

---

## Characteristics of PUT

- Replaces the complete resource
- Usually idempotent
- Requires all updated data

---

# PATCH Method

PATCH updates only part of an existing resource.

Instead of sending the entire profile:

```text
Name : Soham
Age  : 20
City : Mumbai
```

You only send the field that needs updating.

```http
PATCH /profile HTTP/1.1

Age=21
```

Everything else remains unchanged.

---

## PUT vs PATCH

| PUT | PATCH |
|------|--------|
| Replaces entire resource | Updates only selected fields |
| Sends complete data | Sends partial data |
| Usually idempotent | Depends on implementation |

---

# DELETE Method

DELETE removes a resource from the server.

Example:

```http
DELETE /users/15 HTTP/1.1
```

Meaning:

Delete user number 15.

---

## Security Consideration

DELETE requests should always require proper authorization.

Without proper access control, attackers may delete resources belonging to other users.

---

# HEAD Method

HEAD works almost the same as GET.

Difference:

GET returns:

- Headers
- Body

HEAD returns:

- Headers only

No response body is returned.

Useful for:

- Checking if a file exists
- Checking file size
- Checking content type

without downloading the actual file.

---

# OPTIONS Method

OPTIONS asks the server which HTTP methods are supported.

Example:

```http
OPTIONS /api HTTP/1.1
```

Possible response:

```text
Allow:
GET
POST
PUT
DELETE
```

Useful during:

- API testing
- Security assessments
- Understanding server capabilities

---

# Safe Methods

Safe methods should **not modify server data**.

| Method | Safe |
|----------|------|
| GET | ✅ |
| HEAD | ✅ |
| OPTIONS | ✅ |

---

# Unsafe Methods

Unsafe methods may create, modify, or delete data.

| Method | Unsafe |
|----------|---------|
| POST | ✅ |
| PUT | ✅ |
| PATCH | ✅ |
| DELETE | ✅ |

---

# Idempotent Methods

A method is **idempotent** if sending the same request multiple times results in the same final state.

Example:

```http
DELETE /users/15
```

Sending it once deletes the user.

Sending it again still leaves the user deleted.

Final state remains the same.

---

## Idempotent Methods

| Method | Idempotent |
|----------|------------|
| GET | ✅ |
| HEAD | ✅ |
| OPTIONS | ✅ |
| PUT | ✅ |
| DELETE | ✅ |
| PATCH | Depends |
| POST | ❌ |

---

# GET vs POST

| GET | POST |
|------|------|
| Retrieves data | Sends data |
| Parameters in URL | Data in Body |
| Can be bookmarked | Cannot |
| Cached | Usually not cached |
| Suitable for reading | Suitable for submitting |

---

# HTTP Methods at a Glance

| Method | Purpose |
|----------|----------|
| GET | Retrieve data |
| POST | Create or submit data |
| PUT | Replace an existing resource |
| PATCH | Partially update a resource |
| DELETE | Remove a resource |
| HEAD | Retrieve headers only |
| OPTIONS | Discover supported methods |

