# Real-World Examples

| Action | HTTP Method |
|----------|-------------|
| Opening Google | GET |
| Logging into Gmail | POST |
| Updating your profile | PATCH |
| Replacing profile details | PUT |
| Deleting a social media post | DELETE |

---

# Key Points

- Every HTTP request begins with a method.
- The method tells the server what action to perform.
- GET retrieves data.
- POST submits data.
- PUT replaces an entire resource.
- PATCH updates only part of a resource.
- DELETE removes a resource.
- HEAD returns headers only.
- OPTIONS lists supported methods.
- Safe methods should not modify data.
- Idempotent methods produce the same final result when repeated.

---

# Common Interview Questions

### What is an HTTP Method?

An HTTP Method tells the server what action the client wants to perform on a resource.

---

### What is the difference between GET and POST?

GET retrieves data and sends parameters in the URL, whereas POST submits data using the request body.

---

### Difference between PUT and PATCH?

PUT replaces the entire resource, while PATCH updates only selected fields.

---

### Which HTTP methods are considered safe?

GET, HEAD, and OPTIONS.

---

### What is an idempotent method?

An idempotent method produces the same final result even if the same request is sent multiple times.

---

### Why is POST preferred for login?

Because credentials are sent in the request body instead of being exposed in the URL.

